  "timeframe": "15-minute with 5-minute entry refinement",
  "market_context": "Oil's entire day range was contained within a defined range high and range low. London session failed to take out either side of the range, forming failure swings on both ends. Price entered the 8:30/9:30 window with the range still intact.",
  "key_observation": "After London failed to break the range, the 8:30 candle swept both sides of the range, sweeping a prior high; on the 5-minute, a series of up-close candles formed at the new high, providing a change in state of delivery to short into the opposite side of the range.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the 15-minute chart, identify that the day's range is bound by a range high and range low with failure swings on both sides.",
    "Step 2: Observe London session and confirm it did not take out either side of the range, leaving failure swing liquidity intact.",
    "Step 3: At 8:30, note that price swept this side of the range and also swept a prior high, taking buy-side liquidity.",
    "Step 4: On the 15-minute, identify a series of up-close candles, but recognize that on lower time frame a new high formed after a pullback.",
    "Step 5: Drop down to the 5-minute and mark the series of up-close candles at the new high as the change in state of delivery.",
    "Step 6: Plan a short entry with stop placed over/at this swing high, targeting the opposite side of the range for a 1.75 reward-to-risk.",
    "Step 7: Get filled and watch price deliver down to the opposite side of the range."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade got tagged in and price moved to the other side of the range, hitting the 1.75R target successfully.",
  "lessons": "When London fails to take either side of a defined range, the 8:30/9:30 window typically manipulates a side of the range and reverses; using a 5-minute CISD over up-close candles at the swept high offers a precise short entry targeting the opposite side of the range.",
